# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jsonnet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:jsonnet/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:jsonnet/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
[src:jsonnet/google-jsonnet] For an introduction to Jsonnet and documentation, visit our website.
